{"key":"processedPost-9867262","value":{"id":9867262,"first":9854236,"last":9907641,"when":1235632420,"utime":"02/26/09 09:13 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>ScientificClown said:</strong><br />Do you think that still air in the standard shotgun terrarium will ventilate sufficiently? I figured that the air, when not physically circulated, would just sit, and CO2 would stratify forming a layer at the bottom, around the mushrooms/cakes.</blockquote><br />The design is based on the fact that air flows from high pressure to low.&nbsp; There is a high pressure area in the perlite, since it's damp and at a slightly lower temperature due to evaporative cooling.&nbsp; The interior of the terrarium is at a lower pressure due to being slightly warmer because of the substrates and the lighting.&nbsp; This causes a natural circulation that is self sustaining.&nbsp; I've posted the <a href=\"/forums/showflat.php/Number/6880451#Post6880451\" class=\"pp\" target=\"_blank\">engineering behind it</a> several times.<br />RR"}}